        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
              <fr:month>4</fr:month>
              <fr:day>15</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/006W/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>006W</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/lectures/006W/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Negation rules">Negation rules</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>        The last connective to look at is negation.
        Negation is the reason that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex> is so important in NJ.
        Negation, after all, presents the same kind of problem as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex> did: how can we say that something is <html:em>not</html:em> the case, when our proofs are all about assuming or demonstrating what <html:em>is</html:em> the case?
        We saw above how NJ handles that issue in the case of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex>.
        In the case of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg ]]></fr:tex>, NJ simply reuses that same solution, deferring everything back to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex> itself.
</html:p>
            <html:p>        Here, then, are the rules for negation:</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>15</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/007G/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>007G</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/007G/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Negation introduction and elimination:">Negation introduction and elimination:</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
                  <fr:resource hash="63cfb5fb77f4dec01b2a973fa1cbc2e4">
                    <fr:resource-content>
                      <html:img src="/lectures/63cfb5fb77f4dec01b2a973fa1cbc2e4.svg" />
                    </fr:resource-content>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
  \usepackage {bussproofs}
  \newcommand {\DP }{\DisplayProof }
  ]]></fr:resource-source>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
            \AxiomC{\ensuremath{[A]^n\vphantom{|}}}
            \noLine\UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{\ensuremath{}\vdots \vphantom{|}}}
            \noLine
            \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{\bot \vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \neg  I^n:\quad }}
            \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{\neg  A\vphantom{|}}}
            \DP
            \hskip 2cm
            \AxiomC{\ensuremath{\neg  A\vphantom{|}}}
            \AxiomC{\ensuremath{A\vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \neg  E:\quad }}
            \BinaryInfC{\ensuremath{\bot \vphantom{|}}}
            \DP
            ]]></fr:resource-source>
                  </fr:resource>
                </html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>
        Both of these rules involve <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex>.
        You can see <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  I]]></fr:tex> as saying that, if from the assumption of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> we can prove our way to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> itself must be false, so we can discharge the assumption and conclude <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  A]]></fr:tex>.
        And you can see <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  E]]></fr:tex> as saying that any contradiction suffices for MAXIMUM FALSE: if we have proofs of both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, then we can put them together via <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  E]]></fr:tex> to get a proof of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex>.
        (So this gives us yet another way <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex> can get into proofs.)</html:p>
            <html:p>        Consider, for example, the following line of reasoning, inspired by Zeno of Elea, as an argument against the possibility of motion.
Nowadays this is sometimes called one of Zeno's "paradoxes", but it appears that in its original use it was not meant to be a paradox, but simply a straightforward argument for the conclusion that nothing moves.
        Zeno was a follower of Parmenides, and like Parmenides held that everything is one, and does not change.
        Since motion is a kind of change, this includes denying the existence of motion.</html:p>
            <html:p>        
            Suppose someone, call them Mo, has moved some distance <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>.
            Before Mo could move the full distance <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>, they must first have moved a distance of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D/2]]></fr:tex>.
            And before they could have done that, they must first have moved a distance of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D/4]]></fr:tex>.
            Before they could have done that, however, they must first have moved a distance of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D/8]]></fr:tex>.
            And so on, all the way to infinity.
            So Mo must have moved an infinite number of distances.
            But this is impossible: nobody could move an infinite number of distances.
            So the supposition must have been wrong: Mo didn't really move any distance <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> at all.
</html:p>
            <html:p>        Some of this reasoning we don't have the power to capture in NJ.
        In particular, the reasoning that turns on "And so on, all the way to infinity" doesn't seem to nicely fit into the resources we have available.
        But we can still fit the overall shape of this reasoning, in its broad outlines, into NJ.
        Consider, for example, the following proof:</html:p>
            <html:p>
              <fr:resource hash="d787ecf67ed2575c7338c55a8aa6b1b2">
                <fr:resource-content>
                  <html:img src="/lectures/d787ecf67ed2575c7338c55a8aa6b1b2.svg" />
                </fr:resource-content>
                <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
  \usepackage {bussproofs}
  \newcommand {\DP }{\DisplayProof }
  ]]></fr:resource-source>
                <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
            \AxiomC{\ensuremath{\neg  i\vphantom{|}}}
            \AxiomC{\ensuremath{m \rightarrow  i\vphantom{|}}}
            \AxiomC{\ensuremath{[m]^1\vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \rightarrow  E:\quad }}
            \BinaryInfC{\ensuremath{i\vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \neg  E:\quad }}
            \BinaryInfC{\ensuremath{\bot \vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \neg  I^1:\quad }}
            \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{\neg  m\vphantom{|}}}
            \DP
            ]]></fr:resource-source>
              </fr:resource>
            </html:p>
            <html:p>        To see the structure of the Zenoish argument reflected in this proof, think of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> as the claim that Mo moved distance <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex> as the claim that Mo moved an infinite number of distances.
        Then the proof takes two things for granted: that Mo's having moved distance <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> implies Mo having moved an infinite number of distances, and that Mo didn't move an infinite number of distances.
        From these assumptions, the proof concludes that Mo didn't move distance <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>.
        The shape of the proof roughly aligns with the reasoning in the passage: the main difference is that the prose passage gives us some reason to believe <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m \rightarrow  i]]></fr:tex>, where the proof just takes it for granted.
</html:p>
